chemical-substance Terms#

Chemical Substance Domain Ontology#

This ontology provides terms for chemical substances that can be referenced and re-used other resources.

AceticAcid#

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/chemical-substance#substance_b0abf2a1_540e_42fc_b3cf_f5a8a43e591d

altLabel CH3CO2H
elucidation a chemical compound consisting of a carboxylic acid group bonded to a methyl group
wikipediaReference https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acetic_acid
standardInChI InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c1-2(3)4/h1H3,(H,3,4)
wikidataReference https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q47512
molecularFormula C2H4O2
pubChemReference https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/176
hasIUPACName acetic acid
subclassOf OrganicAcid

Acetone#

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/chemical-substance#substance_a065f68b_99ed_4bdd_b568_13158ba1731f

altLabel (CH3)2CO
elucidation a chemical compound consisting of a carbonyl group bonded to two methyl groups
wikipediaReference https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acetone
standardInChI InChI=1S/C3H6O/c1-3(2)4/h1-2H3
wikidataReference https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q49546
molecularFormula C3H6O
pubChemReference https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/180
hasIUPACName propan-2-one
subclassOf OrganicCompound, AproticSolventCompound

Acetonitrile#

Acid#

OrganicAcid#

IRI: https://w3id.org/emmo/domain/chemical-substance#substance_b325bdd7_0adf_4522_a4ef_20cd6929e094

altLabel OrganicAcidCompound
elucidation an organic compound with acidic properties
subclassOf OrganicCompound, Acid
subclasses AceticAcid, MesoxalicAcid, TartaricAcid, LacticAcid, PyruvicAcid, FormicAcid, OxalicAcid, GlycolicAcid, AcrylicAcid, CitricAcid, BenzoicAcid, NitrousAcid, PropionicAcid, TartronicAcid, PentanoicAcid, MalonicAcid, GlycericAcid, HexanoicAcid, HydrazoicAcid, ButanoicAcid, CarbonicAcid, SulfonicAcid, GlyoxylicAcid, MalicAcid, GlycidicAcid

Note

The most common organic acids are the carboxylic acids, whose acidity is associated with their carboxyl group COOH. Sulfonic acids, containing the group SO2OH, are relatively stronger acids. Alcohols, with OH, can act as acids but they are usually very weak.
